node.text:
On a long list of things I miss: waking up to sunrise in Amsterdam, grabbing a stroopwafel in the A.M., getting lost on the canals, realising it’s midday, and maybe its a respectable time to visit a coffee shop.

#Amsterdam #travel #worldofwanderlust

node.text:
Winter is the off season in Tasmania but that’s why I love it most - crisp (okay fine cold) mornings, red wine, early sunsets and late sunrises. Home feels good in this season - the weather and in life. 🌾

Weekend location: @granaryrichmondhill 

#Tasmania #Australia

node.text:
Thank you for your kind messages about my announcement that I’m moving again 🥺🥺 I'm always amazed by how many people take the time to reach out ~ these are the most popular questions I thought I'd answer in one swoop! (more in stories ~ where you can ask your own)

1. When do you move? This month! I'm currently packing up my life in boxes (again lol)

2. What made you decide to move again? It was a comment from J, who said "life can be measured by how many summers you have left ~ what if we lived somewhere where we get more summers".

3. Where will you live? We're looking to buy a house! The market is sooooo crazy rn, I think everywhere in the world. It's a bit scary, but no change/growth happens in the comfort zone. So here's hoping it all falls into place somehow.

4. What is happening to your old house in Tasmania? I sold it! 

5. Is this where you will live forever? Who knows! We are both pretty go-with-the-flow people and I would never say never to moving elsewhere... but I do want to feel settled somewhere so I hope it feels like home. Time will tell!

More in stories x

node.text:
Opened in the late 1880's in Paris' fashionable 6th arrondissement, Saint-Germain-des-Prés, Café de Flore is to this day the epitome of passing time a la Parisian style.⁠
⁠
With a corner location in the heart of Paris' most fashionable arrondissement, it is here where you will find the very essence of café culture in Paris.⁠
⁠
The name, Cafe de Flore, is taken from a sculpture of Flora, the goddess of flowers and the season of spring in Roman mythology, located on the opposite side of the boulevard.⁠
⁠
And with post-war regulars such as Ernest Hemingway and Simone de Beauvoir, who are we to say this Parisian institution will ever go out of style? Click the link in bio to discover our Solo Girls' Guide to Paris.⁠
⁠
📷 @chloecleroux ⁠
⁠
⁠
—⁠
⁠

node.text: This year was unexpectedly the best one yet and surprisingly I didn’t even have to go anywhere for that to be so 🥲 Feeling an odd sense of gratitude for being forced to stay still and enjoy the quiet calmness ~ realising there are so many ordinary joys in just living. 🕊

node.text:
Got to explore an island off an island this week for our last exploration in Tasmania before (yet another) move! Thanks to @taswalkingco for the 4 day sail/walk experience, I finally got to see the Maria Island painted cliffs up close.

All my life Tasmania has been home, despite many attempts to leave 🥲 but each time I’ve felt less and less settled here, like maybe I’ve seen too much or travelled too far to feel that this is could be ~home~ forever. 

Maybe one day, maybe not ever. But I’m a big believer in following your gut and knowing when it’s time to stay or time to go. Excited to share with you all where home will be next!
